 ## Risks / things to watch
 
-- **The seed-SHA chicken-and-egg.** The chosen pattern (write the
-  seed SHA to a file inside the volume; service entrypoint falls
-  back to reading it) is the simplest. It does mean the
-  orchestrator/planner needs a small env-var-or-file-fallback shim
-  in their CLIs. An alternative — thread the seed SHA in via a
-  generated env file — requires a *second* `compose up` (one to
-  initialize the repo, one to start the rest) since the seed SHA
-  isn't known on the first up. The chosen pattern keeps it to one
-  `compose up`.
-
-  Codex will likely push back on adding a CLI fallback path. If so:
-  the alternative is to update setup-experiment to run the seed
-  commit on the host before `compose up`, writing the SHA into the
-  generated `.env` synchronously. That requires the host to have
-  `git` installed (CI does; macOS has it via Xcode CLI tools) and
-  the bare repo to live somewhere accessible from inside the
-  container. Mounting a host directory into the named volume is
-  fragile across platforms; mounting the host directory directly
-  (`bind:` mount) trades the named-volume pattern for host-coupling.
-  My current call: keep the in-volume `SEED_SHA` file; document the
-  alternative; let codex decide.
-
 - **`uv sync --frozen` in Docker requires `uv.lock`.** If the lock
   file ever becomes stale relative to `pyproject.toml`, `--frozen`
   fails the build. We commit `uv.lock`; the existing `python-lint`
